INSERT INTO `messages` VALUES (1,4,'assistant','Hi Laura,  \n\nWelcome back! Based on our recent diagnostic, here are the top three priorities to get Stepping Into Your Power sale-ready and set you up for scalable growth:\n\n1. M8 Due Diligence Preparation (Red – Rank 1)  \n   • Why: You don’t yet have a strategic business plan or centralised data-room.  \n   • Quick win: Create a secure folder structure for due diligence documents (financial, legal, operations, HR, IP).\n\n2. M4 People (Red – Rank 2)  \n   • Why: There are no formal HR policies, no staff register or key-employee designations.  \n   • Quick win: Compile a complete staff list (even if it’s just you and future hires) with roles, start dates and “key-employee” flags.\n\n3. M3 Owner Dependency & Operations (Red – Rank 3)  \n   • Why: The business runs entirely on your shoulders, with no documented processes.  \n   • Quick win: Document your daily and periodic duties, then map out simple standard operating procedures (SOPs).\n\nAll other modules (customer segmentation, legal docs, financial reporting, brand consistency and tax compliance) are Amber/Green and can follow once these reds are tackled.\n\nNext steps—what would you like to focus on first? For example:  \n– Drafting your due-diligence folder structure (I can share a template)  \n– Working through a basic SOP for your workshop delivery and 1:1 client process  \n– Building a “people register” that will grow as you bring on contractors or employees  \n\nLet me know which you’d prefer, or if you’d like to address more than one area in parallel. Once you choose, I’ll guide you through a simple, step-by-step plan.',NULL,NULL,'2025-05-26 21:51:59','2025-05-26 21:51:59'),(2,4,'user','Hey Trinity. You mention business plan as the first priority. WHy is that, given the high owner dependency, wouldn\'t that be the focus instead? Also - there are no staff in this business as yet',NULL,NULL,'2025-05-26 21:53:00','2025-05-26 21:53:00'),(3,4,'assistant','Good questions, Laura. Let me unpack the reasoning:\n\n1. Why a strategic business plan sits at the top  \n  • Foundation for everything else: A clear plan defines your vision, goals, target markets, key offerings and growth strategy. Without that north-star, every other piece (processes, people, marketing) can drift off course.  \n  • Due diligence readiness: Buyers look first for evidence you know where you’re heading and how you’ll get there. A one-page plan or strategy summary anchors your data room and shows you’ve thought things through.  \n  • Enabler for reducing owner dependency: Once you’ve written down your strategy and objectives, it becomes much easier to document the processes and routines that support them—and then hand those over to someone else down the track.\n\n2. How owner dependency fits in  \n  • We rank “owner dependency & operations” highly because 100% reliance on you is a major risk for a buyer. But the very first step to solving that is knowing which processes align to which strategic objectives—hence the plan comes first.  \n  • With a plan in place, you can ask: “Which workshop steps, client-onboarding tasks or marketing activities can I delegate?” That directly feeds into your SOPs and handover materials.\n\n3. What about the “People” module when you have no staff?  \n  • Even as a sole operator, you can use that module to:  \n    – Document your own role, hours and key responsibilities (we call that a “people register”).  \n    – Sketch out future roles or contractor engagements you’ll need to hit your plan.  \n    – Flag “key roles” (e.g., workshop facilitator, client manager, marketing lead) so you know what to hire or contract next.\n\nNext steps  \n  • Would you like a simple template for a one-page strategic plan? We can break it into Vision, Objectives, Key Strategies and KPIs—easy to draft in 30–45 minutes.  \n  • Once that’s done, we can map your daily/periodic duties to each strategic pillar, which immediately reduces owner dependency and feeds directly into your SOPs.  \n\nWhich of those sounds most helpful to you right now?','{\"id\":\"chatcmpl-Bba2fLO9uGzSJZ5j6UJEHBSzObpel\",\"object\":\"chat.completion\",\"created\":1748296381,\"model\":\"o4-mini-2025-04-16\",\"choices\":[{\"index\":0,\"message\":{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"Good questions, Laura. Let me unpack the reasoning:\\n\\n1. Why a strategic business plan sits at the top  \\n  \\u2022 Foundation for everything else: A clear plan defines your vision, goals, target markets, key offerings and growth strategy. Without that north-star, every other piece (processes, people, marketing) can drift off course.  \\n  \\u2022 Due diligence readiness: Buyers look first for evidence you know where you\\u2019re heading and how you\\u2019ll get there. A one-page plan or strategy summary anchors your data room and shows you\\u2019ve thought things through.  \\n  \\u2022 Enabler for reducing owner dependency: Once you\\u2019ve written down your strategy and objectives, it becomes much easier to document the processes and routines that support them\\u2014and then hand those over to someone else down the track.\\n\\n2. How owner dependency fits in  \\n  \\u2022 We rank \\u201cowner dependency & operations\\u201d highly because 100% reliance on you is a major risk for a buyer. But the very first step to solving that is knowing which processes align to which strategic objectives\\u2014hence the plan comes first.  \\n  \\u2022 With a plan in place, you can ask: \\u201cWhich workshop steps, client-onboarding tasks or marketing activities can I delegate?\\u201d That directly feeds into your SOPs and handover materials.\\n\\n3. What about the \\u201cPeople\\u201d module when you have no staff?  \\n  \\u2022 Even as a sole operator, you can use that module to:  \\n    \\u2013 Document your own role, hours and key responsibilities (we call that a \\u201cpeople register\\u201d).  \\n    \\u2013 Sketch out future roles or contractor engagements you\\u2019ll need to hit your plan.  \\n    \\u2013 Flag \\u201ckey roles\\u201d (e.g., workshop facilitator, client manager, marketing lead) so you know what to hire or contract next.\\n\\nNext steps  \\n  \\u2022 Would you like a simple template for a one-page strategic plan? We can break it into Vision, Objectives, Key Strategies and KPIs\\u2014easy to draft in 30\\u201345 minutes.  \\n  \\u2022 Once that\\u2019s done, we can map your daily\\/periodic duties to each strategic pillar, which immediately reduces owner dependency and feeds directly into your SOPs.  \\n\\nWhich of those sounds most helpful to you right now?\",\"refusal\":null,\"annotations\":[]},\"finish_reason\":\"stop\"}],\"usage\":{\"prompt_tokens\":7948,\"completion_tokens\":866,\"total_tokens\":8814,\"prompt_tokens_details\":{\"cached_tokens\":0,\"audio_tokens\":0},\"completion_tokens_details\":{\"reasoning_tokens\":384,\"audio_tokens\":0,\"accepted_prediction_tokens\":0,\"rejected_prediction_tokens\":0}},\"service_tier\":\"default\",\"system_fingerprint\":null}','{\"model\":\"o4-mini-2025-04-16\",\"usage\":{\"prompt_tokens\":7948,\"completion_tokens\":866,\"total_tokens\":8814,\"prompt_tokens_details\":{\"cached_tokens\":0,\"audio_tokens\":0},\"completion_tokens_details\":{\"reasoning_tokens\":384,\"audio_tokens\":0,\"accepted_prediction_tokens\":0,\"rejected_prediction_tokens\":0}}}','2025-05-26 21:53:09','2025-05-26 21:53:09'),(4,6,'assistant','Hello Peter, it’s a pleasure to meet you. I’m Trinity, your business advisor. How can I assist you today? Are there specific areas of your business you’d like to discuss—strategy, operations, marketing, finance or something else entirely?',NULL,NULL,'2025-06-03 01:51:26','2025-06-03 01:51:26'),(5,6,'user','Hey Trinity - you mentioned in the report that we have a reliance on the owners - how do we move forward addresisng this?',NULL,NULL,'2025-06-03 01:52:02','2025-06-03 01:52:02'),(6,6,'assistant','To tackle owner-dependence you’ll want a structured approach that shifts critical knowledge and decision-making into your team and processes. Let’s break it into four stages:\n\n1. Map and Prioritise  \n  • Which activities today couldn’t run without an owner? (e.g. key client negotiations, financial approvals, day-to-day ops, product decisions)  \n  • Of those, which carry the greatest risk if an owner is unavailable?\n\n2. Document and Systematise  \n  • For each critical activity, write a simple Standard Operating Procedure (SOP) or checklist.  \n  • Capture decision criteria (“if revenue dips 10%, trigger a marketing push,” “price-cut approval needs these three data points,” etc.).  \n  • Store these in a shareable, version-controlled place (cloud folder or simple intranet).\n\n3. Define Roles & Delegate  \n  • Group tasks into clear roles or “buckets.” For example:  \n     – Operations lead handles daily scheduling, supplier liaison and stock-reorder points  \n     – Finance lead manages invoicing, payroll and budget monitoring  \n     – Sales lead owns proposals, client follow-ups and performance reporting  \n  • Assess current team strengths—can someone be promoted or trained into each bucket? If not, consider targeted hiring.\n\n4. Train, Empower & Monitor  \n  • Run hands-on training sessions: have the owner coach a nominated team member through each SOP until they can operate independently.  \n  • Establish simple KPIs or dashboards so you and the new role take a “hands-off” view but still see results (e.g. order fulfilment rate, days-sales-outstanding, client satisfaction scores).  \n  • Build in regular check-ins (weekly then monthly) so you can troubleshoot until you have full confidence in the team.\n\nNext Steps—A Few Quick Questions  \n  1. Which functions do you feel you and any co-owner spend most time on today?  \n  2. How large is your team, and do you already have any managers or team leads?  \n  3. What’s your ideal timeline for reducing owner involvement (3, 6 or 12 months)?\n\nWith those details I can suggest a more tailored roadmap, including any quick-win hires or system tools you might need.','{\"id\":\"chatcmpl-BeB6pTOkhBGaWX4tsv4XCbzTd1Wav\",\"object\":\"chat.completion\",\"created\":1748915523,\"model\":\"o4-mini-2025-04-16\",\"choices\":[{\"index\":0,\"message\":{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"To tackle owner-dependence you\\u2019ll want a structured approach that shifts critical knowledge and decision-making into your team and processes. Let\\u2019s break it into four stages:\\n\\n1. Map and Prioritise  \\n  \\u2022 Which activities today couldn\\u2019t run without an owner? (e.g. key client negotiations, financial approvals, day-to-day ops, product decisions)  \\n  \\u2022 Of those, which carry the greatest risk if an owner is unavailable?\\n\\n2. Document and Systematise  \\n  \\u2022 For each critical activity, write a simple Standard Operating Procedure (SOP) or checklist.  \\n  \\u2022 Capture decision criteria (\\u201cif revenue dips 10%, trigger a marketing push,\\u201d \\u201cprice-cut approval needs these three data points,\\u201d etc.).  \\n  \\u2022 Store these in a shareable, version-controlled place (cloud folder or simple intranet).\\n\\n3. Define Roles & Delegate  \\n  \\u2022 Group tasks into clear roles or \\u201cbuckets.\\u201d For example:  \\n     \\u2013 Operations lead handles daily scheduling, supplier liaison and stock-reorder points  \\n     \\u2013 Finance lead manages invoicing, payroll and budget monitoring  \\n     \\u2013 Sales lead owns proposals, client follow-ups and performance reporting  \\n  \\u2022 Assess current team strengths\\u2014can someone be promoted or trained into each bucket? If not, consider targeted hiring.\\n\\n4. Train, Empower & Monitor  \\n  \\u2022 Run hands-on training sessions: have the owner coach a nominated team member through each SOP until they can operate independently.  \\n  \\u2022 Establish simple KPIs or dashboards so you and the new role take a \\u201chands-off\\u201d view but still see results (e.g. order fulfilment rate, days-sales-outstanding, client satisfaction scores).  \\n  \\u2022 Build in regular check-ins (weekly then monthly) so you can troubleshoot until you have full confidence in the team.\\n\\nNext Steps\\u2014A Few Quick Questions  \\n  1. Which functions do you feel you and any co-owner spend most time on today?  \\n  2. How large is your team, and do you already have any managers or team leads?  \\n  3. What\\u2019s your ideal timeline for reducing owner involvement (3, 6 or 12 months)?\\n\\nWith those details I can suggest a more tailored roadmap, including any quick-win hires or system tools you might need.\",\"refusal\":null,\"annotations\":[]},\"finish_reason\":\"stop\"}],\"usage\":{\"prompt_tokens\":575,\"completion_tokens\":874,\"total_tokens\":1449,\"prompt_tokens_details\":{\"cached_tokens\":0,\"audio_tokens\":0},\"completion_tokens_details\":{\"reasoning_tokens\":384,\"audio_tokens\":0,\"accepted_prediction_tokens\":0,\"rejected_prediction_tokens\":0}},\"service_tier\":\"default\",\"system_fingerprint\":null}','{\"model\":\"o4-mini-2025-04-16\",\"usage\":{\"prompt_tokens\":575,\"completion_tokens\":874,\"total_tokens\":1449,\"prompt_tokens_details\":{\"cached_tokens\":0,\"audio_tokens\":0},\"completion_tokens_details\":{\"reasoning_tokens\":384,\"audio_tokens\":0,\"accepted_prediction_tokens\":0,\"rejected_prediction_tokens\":0}}}','2025-06-03 01:52:13','2025-06-03 01:52:13'),(7,6,'user','Can you givce me the steps to understand roles and responsibilities?',NULL,NULL,'2025-06-03 01:53:10','2025-06-03 01:53:10'),(8,6,'assistant','Here’s a clear, step-by-step process to map out and clarify roles and responsibilities in your business:\n\n1. List Core Activities  \n   • Pull together the key processes and tasks your business performs daily, weekly and monthly (e.g. order fulfilment, client quotes, supplier management, payroll, safety compliance).  \n2. Group Tasks into Functional Buckets  \n   • Cluster related tasks into broad functions or “role buckets” such as Operations, Finance, Sales, HR, Quality & Safety, Maintenance, IT.  \n3. Draft Preliminary Role Outlines  \n   • For each function, sketch a role title and bullet-point its main duties. Don’t worry about wording yet—this is just your first draft.  \n4. Build a RACI Matrix  \n   • Create a simple table with Process/Task down the left and Roles across the top.  \n   • For each cell, assign:  \n     – R (Responsible): who does the work  \n     – A (Accountable): who signs off  \n     – C (Consulted): who advises  \n     – I (Informed): who needs updates  \n5. Validate with Stakeholders  \n   • Workshop the draft RACI with those owners, managers and key employees who perform or supervise these tasks. Capture any overlaps or gaps.  \n6. Finalise Job Descriptions  \n   • Turn each approved role outline into a formal job description: purpose, key duties, KPIs, qualifications or licences required.  \n7. Define Reporting Lines & Authorities  \n   • Clarify who reports to whom, approval thresholds (e.g. spending limits, contract sign-off) and escalation paths.  \n8. Communicate & Publish  \n   • Share the RACI chart, org chart and job descriptions in a common place (intranet or shared drive). Hold a team meeting to explain them and answer questions.  \n9. Review Regularly  \n   • Schedule a six-monthly check-in to update roles as processes evolve, new systems launch or your business structure changes.\n\nNext steps:  \n• Pick one function (e.g. Finance) and run through steps 1–4 as a pilot.  \n• Let me know if you’d like a template for the RACI matrix or a sample job description outline.','{\"id\":\"chatcmpl-BeB7ujGFb2zWj4uRH1rd0WwTJ0Pgr\",\"object\":\"chat.completion\",\"created\":1748915590,\"model\":\"o4-mini-2025-04-16\",\"choices\":[{\"index\":0,\"message\":{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"Here\\u2019s a clear, step-by-step process to map out and clarify roles and responsibilities in your business:\\n\\n1. List Core Activi